In [525]:
df = df_county_data.groupby(by=['State','Date'],as_index=False).sum()

state_list = []
population_list = []
total_pop = sum(df['Population'].values.tolist())
other_pop = 0 
for state, population in zip(df['State'].values.tolist(),df['Population'].values.tolist()):
    if((population *100 / total_pop) > 2):
        state_list.append(state)
        population_list.append(population)
    else:
        other_pop += population
        
state_list.append('Other')
population_list.append(other_pop)

labels = state_list

fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,8))
ax1.pie(population_list, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%',
        shadow=True, startangle=90)
ax1.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
ax1.legend(labels,
          title="Lables",
          loc="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
plt.title("U.S. Population Distribution in 1990\n", bbox={'facecolor':'0.8', 'pad':5})
plt.show()

We suggest a metric to understand how stable is the stock market in a current year.¶

In the graph you can see a scatter plot for each year from 2008 to 20018

each point in the graph is a change by % in a day in that year.

if we notice a big cluster around change = 0% we can see that overall the year was pretty stable.

As we know in 2008 there was a big break down in the stock market --> in the graph we can see that the cluster is very scattered.

# will find what features are useless.

# If some columns has missing data by more than 50% , we drop those columns.
# for that task we will define a threshold that will be initialized to be the length of the column devided by 2 {50%}.

# pandas.DataFrame.dropna --> Remove missing values.

print('columns before dropping missing values columns:')
print(df_Life_Expectancy_xlsx_copy.columns)
print('\n\n')


# print('\ndata frame df_Life_Expectancy_xlsx_copy')
# print('amount of columns before change ')
# print(len(df_Life_Expectancy_xlsx_copy.columns))
df_Life_Expectancy_xlsx_copy.dropna(thresh=len(df_Life_Expectancy_xlsx_copy.columns.tolist())/3, axis=0, inplace=True)

    if(isinstance(list(x)[0], (int, np.integer))):
        return sum(list((x)))       
    else:
        if(len(set(x)) ==1):
            return list(x)[0]
        else:
            return list(set(x))

Creating a measure for voter turnout Finding total elections to house in the given state, and divide it by the ammount of votes for presidency in that state and year. Notice that presidency vote are always higher.¶

  1. Added a feature of land area --> we might see some trends in big landed areas. Useful to understand if in big areas the voting distribtution is uniform or rather different.
  1. Added feature of water area that stands for --> – the area in square kilometers that is covered by water all year long.

We think that maybe the closeness to water resources might lead to vote to some candidate. As we know water is a place then might be a good place for tourism or shipping. Those results might help us to get a better overview conducting this feature too.

  1. Added the popultaion as a feature to indicate if the size of the population may lead to unidormic voting. We estimate that this phenomena might occure due to the strict rules in big states.

• Population – population estimates for the county in 1990.

  1. water_Area_divided_by_land --> try to fine some pattern by the relationship within the amount of land area to the amount of water area within some country in the data frame
  1. land_by_population --> find the density of the population in a given country and see how that may effect the results of the election.

We might assume that more dense areas may lead to group voting.

  1. water by population --> we may suggest that in a given area there might be some lack of resources that may lead to vote for some candidate with is more liberal and thinks about the poor people. In the other hand we can check if countries with a lot of water (is a resource) may vote to a leader that believes in a free market spirit.

1. Random Forest Regressor - Regressor¶

In [584]:
# define model
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_jobs=-1, random_state=10)

# define parameter grid
parameters_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5],
    'min_samples_leaf': [2, 8],
    'n_estimators': [20, 50],
    'max_features': [2, 4]
}

# define grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_grid=parameters_grid, cv=10)

# fit estimator
grid_search.fit(X_train_Section_C, y_train_Section_C)

# get best estimator
best = grid_search.best_estimator_
# predict
y_pred = best.predict(X_test_Section_C)
# calculate MSE
MSE = round(mean_squared_error(y_test_Section_C, y_pred), 3)
print('MSE :',MSE)
df_C = pd.DataFrame([MSE]).T
df_C = df_C.rename(index={0: 'Random Forest Regressor'}, columns={0: 'MSE'})

# get feature importance
imp = pd.DataFrame(grid_search.best_estimator_.fit(X_train_Section_C, y_train_Section_C).feature_importances_,
                   index=X_train_Section_C.columns, columns=['Importance']).sort_values('Importance')

MSE : 0.003

By comparing the models performence we get a low MSE value. We might face over fittig to our models.

the lower the value the better and 0 means the model is perfect.

We might want to use more data to perform a larger range of results.

Or doing iterativley more models with different data, create a avg of those models for each kind {reduce over fitting}.
